                                      ... Even if building a session layer
	interface means a simple routine that, given an array of addresses,
	sorts them based on locally configured information about "preferred"
	networks, this would at least give us the hooks to build something
	a little more sophisticated later (perhaps load sensitive or time-
	of-day routing, since rush hour here is sleepy-time there).

	-Philip

The Host Requirements RFC 1123 strongly suggests such locally
configured information for ordering alternate addresses (section 6.1.3.4
of RFC-1123), to be included in the name-&gt;host transformation provided
by the DNS client program.  [I would not called that a "session layer"
function, but oerhaps there is no other obvious place to put it in
the ISO model].

The Host Requirements Working Group did not feel secure enough about
this mechanism to actually require it (nobody really likes to be
dependent upon configuration data, that network administrators have to
set and may set wrong), but hoped that implementors will take the
suggestion seriously, since there is no apparent alternative.

Bob Braden

